Used Cars Price Prediction¶

Problem Definition¶

The Context:¶

  • Why is this problem important to solve?

The objective:¶

  • What is the intended goal?

The key questions:¶

  • What are the key questions that need to be answered?

The problem formulation:¶

  • What is it that we are trying to solve using data science?

Data Dictionary¶

S.No. : Serial Number

Name : Name of the car which includes Brand name and Model name

Location : The location in which the car is being sold or is available for purchase (Cities)

Year : Manufacturing year of the car

Kilometers_driven : The total kilometers driven in the car by the previous owner(s) in KM

Fuel_Type : The type of fuel used by the car (Petrol, Diesel, Electric, CNG, LPG)

Transmission : The type of transmission used by the car (Automatic / Manual)

Owner : Type of ownership

Mileage : The standard mileage offered by the car company in kmpl or km/kg

Engine : The displacement volume of the engine in CC

Power : The maximum power of the engine in bhp

Seats : The number of seats in the car

New_Price : The price of a new car of the same model in INR 100,000

Price : The price of the used car in INR 100,000 (Target Variable)

Problem Definition¶

The Context:¶

Predicting the price of used cars is crucial for the Cars 4U startup to set competitive and profitable prices. This problem is important because an accurate pricing model can optimize sales, enhance customer satisfaction, and improve the company's overall profitability.

The Objective:¶

The goal is to develop a predictive model that estimates the price of used cars based on their characteristics, and to identify a differential pricing strategy that can be applied to various car segments.

The Key Questions:¶

  • What are the key factors that influence the price of a used car?
  • How can we preprocess the data to improve model accuracy?
  • What machine learning models best predict used car prices?
  • How can the model be utilized to implement a profitable pricing strategy?

The Problem Formulation:¶

Using data science, we aim to predict the price of used cars by analyzing various features such as the car's age, mileage, brand, and other attributes. The data will be explored, cleaned, and modeled to achieve this goal.

Feature Engineering¶

Think about it:

The Name column in the current format might not be very useful in our analysis. Since the name contains both the brand name and the model name of the vehicle, the column would have too many unique values to be useful in prediction. Can we extract that information from that column?

Hint:

With 2041 unique names, car names are not going to be great predictors of the price in our current data. But we can process this column to extract important information for example brand name.

Missing Value Treatment¶

Since all the missing features are numerical in nature, they can be filled in with the median of the other values in same features. The feature New_price has 14% missing data and the variable Price is the target variable so they will be dropped.

# a. Imputing missing values in 'Mileage' with the median value
df['Mileage'].fillna(df['Mileage'].median(), inplace=True)

# b. Imputing missing values in 'Engine' with the median value
df['Engine'].fillna(df['Engine'].median(), inplace=True)

# c. Imputing missing values in 'Power' with the median value
df['Power'].fillna(df['Power'].median(), inplace=True)

# d. Imputing missing values in 'Seats' with the median value
df['Seats'].fillna(df['Seats'].median(), inplace=True)

# e. Dropping the 'New_price' column due to high number of missing values
df.drop(columns=['New_price'], inplace=True)

#Extracting brand name from name
df['Brand'] = df['Name'].apply(lambda x: x.split()[0])

# Standardizing the 'Brand' column
df['Brand'] = df['Brand'].str.strip()  # Removing any leading/trailing whitespace
df['Brand'] = df['Brand'].str.title()  # Converting to title case to ensure consistency

# Correcting specific brand names
df['Brand'].replace({
    'Isuzu': 'Isuzu',  # Combine Isuzu and ISUZU
    'ISUZU': 'Isuzu',
    'Hindustan': 'Hindustan Motors',
    'Land': 'Land Rover'  # If "Land" refers to Land Rover
}, inplace=True)

In [65]:
# Separating the complete cases from the ones with missing 'Price'
complete_df = df[df['Price'].notnull()]
missing_df = df[df['Price'].isnull()]

# Features to use for predicting 'Price'
features = ['Year', 'Kilometers_Driven', 'Mileage', 'Engine', 'Power', 'Seats',
            'Fuel_Type', 'Transmission', 'Owner_Type', 'Location', 'Brand']

# One-hot encoding of categorical variables
X_train = pd.get_dummies(complete_df[features], drop_first=True)
y_train = complete_df['Price']

# Training a model to predict missing prices
rf = RandomForestRegressor(random_state=42)
rf.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Predicting the missing prices using .loc[] to avoid the warning
X_missing = pd.get_dummies(missing_df[features], drop_first=True).reindex(columns=X_train.columns, fill_value=0)
missing_df.loc[:, 'Price'] = rf.predict(X_missing)

# Combining the imputed data with the original data
df_imputed = pd.concat([complete_df, missing_df])

# Checking if all missing values are handled
df_imputed.isnull().sum()

Observations from the Summary Statistics:¶

Numerical Variables:¶

Year: The cars in the dataset range from 1996 to 2019, with a mean manufacturing year of around 2013. This indicates that most of the cars are relatively recent.

Kilometers_Driven: The Kilometers_Driven ranges from 1,710 km to 6,500,000 km, with a mean of 85,699 km.

Mileage: Mileage values range from 0 to 35.54 kmpl/km/kg with an average of 18.14. The minimum value of 0 suggests missing or incorrect data.

Engine: The engine size ranges from 72 CC to 5998 CC, with an average around 1615 CC. This range appears reasonable.

Power: The power ranges from 34 bhp to 616 bhp, with an average of 112 bhp.

Seats: The number of seats ranges from 2 to 10, with a typical value of 5. This is expected as most passenger vehicles typically have 4-5 seats.

Price: The price of used cars ranges from 0.44 lakhs to 160 lakhs, with a mean price of 9.37 lakhs.

Categorical Variables:¶

Location: The dataset covers 11 different locations, with Mumbai being the most frequent location, appearing 949 times.

Fuel_Type: There are 5 different fuel types, with Diesel being the most common, appearing 3852 times.

Transmission: There are 2 types of transmission, with Manual being the most common, appearing 5204times.

Owner_Type: There are 4 types of ownership, with the First owner being the most common, appearing 5952 times.

Brand: The dataset includes 32 different car brands, with Maruti being the most common brand, appearing 1444 times.

Numerical Variables:

Year: The distribution is slightly left-skewed. This suggests that most cars in the dataset are relatively new, but this skewness is not extreme and may not require log transformation.

Kilometers_Driven: The distribution is right-skewed, indicating that most cars have lower mileage, with a few having very high mileage.

Mileage: The distribution is slightly left-skewed, showing that most cars have mileage in the typical range, with few cars having lower mileage.

Engine: This variable is moderately right-skewed, suggesting that while most cars have engine sizes in the common range, some cars have significantly larger engines.

Power: The distribution is right-skewed, indicating that most cars have moderate power, with a few high-performance vehicles.

Seats: This variable is highly right-skewed, with the majority of cars having 5 seats, and very few having more or fewer seats.

Price: The distribution is highly right-skewed, indicating that most cars are priced lower, with a few high-value outliers.

In [78]:
# Applying log transformation to the skewed numerical variables
log_transformed_cols = ['Kilometers_Driven', 'Engine', 'Power', 'Seats', 'Price']

for col in log_transformed_cols:
    df_cleaned[col + '_log'] = np.log1p(df_cleaned[col])  # log1p is used to handle zero values

# Visualizing the transformed variables
df_cleaned[[col + '_log' for col in log_transformed_cols]].hist(bins=15, figsize=(15, 10))
plt.suptitle('Histograms of Log Transformed Numerical Variables')
plt.show()

Normalization: For most variables, log transformation has helped in normalizing the distributions, making them more symmetric and reducing the impact of outliers.

Model Performance: The improved distribution should contribute to better model performance, especially for linear models that assume normally distributed residuals.

Seats: For Seats, the log transformation didn't have a significant impact. The variable is still heavily skewed towards a single value (likely 5 seats).

Dealing with outliers

In [84]:
# Define a function to remove outliers based on IQR for each location
def remove_outliers_iqr(df, column, group_by_col):
    # Calculate Q1, Q3, and IQR for each group
    Q1 = df.groupby(group_by_col)[column].transform(lambda x: x.quantile(0.25))
    Q3 = df.groupby(group_by_col)[column].transform(lambda x: x.quantile(0.75))
    IQR = Q3 - Q1

    # Define the lower and upper bounds for outliers
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

    # Filter out outliers
    df_outliers_removed = df[(df[column] >= lower_bound) & (df[column] <= upper_bound)]

    return df_outliers_removed

# Apply the function to remove outliers in the 'Price' column grouped by 'Location'
df_cleaned_no_outliers = remove_outliers_iqr(df_cleaned, 'Price', 'Location')

# Check the shape of the DataFrame before and after removing outliers
print(f"Original shape: {df_cleaned.shape}")
print(f"Shape after removing outliers: {df_cleaned_no_outliers.shape}")

# View the updated box plot to verify outlier removal
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
sns.boxplot(x='Location', y='Price', data=df_cleaned_no_outliers)
plt.title('Box Plot of Price by Location After Removing Outliers')
plt.show()

Original shape: (7172, 12)
Shape after removing outliers: (6992, 12)

Important Insights from EDA and Data Preprocessing¶

What are the the most important observations and insights from the data based on the EDA and Data Preprocessing performed?

  1. Data Structure and Missing Values:

Missing Values:

Several features had missing values, including Mileage, Engine, Power, Seats, and Price. The New_Price column had a significant amount of missing data and was dropped due to its limited utility. Missing values in Price (the target variable) were imputed using a Random Forest model trained on the available data. Data Cleaning: Outliers and unrealistic data points (e.g., extremely high or low values) were identified and removed to ensure a cleaner dataset. The Seats column was found to have minimal variation, with most cars having 5 seats, making it less useful for modeling.

  1. Feature Extraction:

Name Column: The Name column, which contained both the brand and model of the car, was broken down to extract the Brand and Model of the car. This transformation reduced the complexity of the dataset and provided more meaningful features for analysis.

Log Transformation: Several features, including Price, Kilometers_Driven, and Power, were log-transformed to address skewness and improve the distribution of the data. This transformation helped normalize the data, making it more suitable for modeling.

  1. Feature Relationships:

Correlation Analysis:

The correlation heatmap revealed that Power and Engine have the highest positive correlations with Price, making them strong predictors. Kilometers_Driven had a weak negative correlation with Price, indicating that cars with higher mileage tend to be priced lower, but this relationship is not as strong as for other features. Categorical Variables: The Location variable showed significant variability in car prices across different cities, suggesting that regional factors play a role in determining used car prices. The Fuel_Type variable was also an important categorical feature, with diesel cars being the most common in the dataset.

  1. Data Distribution:

Skewness:

Features like Price, Power, and Kilometers_Driven were found to be skewed, which was addressed through log transformation. This step helped in making the data more symmetric, reducing the impact of outliers, and improving model performance.

Box Plot Insights: The box plot of Price by Location highlighted regional differences in pricing, with cities like Bangalore and Coimbatore showing higher median prices compared to others like Pune and Ahmedabad. This suggests the need for a differential pricing strategy based on location.

  1. Data Representation:

Categorical Features:

The dataset contains several categorical variables, such as Brand, Fuel_Type, and Location, which will need to be encoded (e.g., using one-hot encoding) before being used in predictive models. Numeric Features: After the log transformation, the distributions of key numeric features became more normal-like, which is beneficial for linear modeling techniques.

    In [94]:
    def calculate_metrics(y_true, y_pred, model_name):
    mse = mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred)
    mae = mean_absolute_error(y_true, y_pred)
    r2 = r2_score(y_true, y_pred)
    return pd.DataFrame({'Model': [model_name], 'MSE': [mse], 'MAE': [mae], 'R2': [r2]})

# Initializing an empty DataFrame to store the results
results_df = pd.DataFrame()

# Calculating metrics for Linear Regression
y_pred_linear = linear_model.predict(X_test)
results_df = pd.concat([results_df, calculate_metrics(y_test, y_pred_linear, 'Linear Regression')], ignore_index=True)

# Calculating metrics for Ridge Regression
y_pred_ridge = ridge_model.predict(X_test)
results_df = pd.concat([results_df, calculate_metrics(y_test, y_pred_ridge, 'Ridge Regression')], ignore_index=True)

# Calculating metrics for Lasso Regression
y_pred_lasso = lasso_model.predict(X_test)
results_df = pd.concat([results_df, calculate_metrics(y_test, y_pred_lasso, 'Lasso Regression')], ignore_index=True)

# Calculating metrics for Decision Tree Regression
y_pred_tree = tree_model.predict(X_test)
results_df = pd.concat([results_df, calculate_metrics(y_test, y_pred_tree, 'Decision Tree Regression')], ignore_index=True)

# Calculating metrics for Random Forest Regression
y_pred_forest = forest_model.predict(X_test)
results_df = pd.concat([results_df, calculate_metrics(y_test, y_pred_forest, 'Random Forest Regression')], ignore_index=True)

    Conclusions and Recommendations¶

    1. Comparison of various techniques and their relative performance based on chosen Metric (Measure of success):

    • How do different techniques perform? Which one is performing relatively better? Is there scope to improve the performance further?

    2. Refined insights:

    • What are the most meaningful insights relevant to the problem?

    • What model do you propose to be adopted? Why is this the best solution to adopt?

    Conclusion¶

    1. Comparison of Various Techniques:¶

    Linear Regression: This model had a reasonable performance, but it was outperformed by more complex models. Given its simplicity, it's easier to interpret but may not capture complex relationships in the data.

    Ridge and Lasso Regression: These models help in managing multicollinearity by applying regularization. They performed slightly better than Linear Regression but still lagged behind tree-based methods.

    Decision Tree: After hyperparameter tuning, the Decision Tree showed improved performance, with an R of approximately 0.91. It captures non-linear relationships but can be prone to overfitting.

    Random Forest: This ensemble method was the best-performing model, even before tuning. After hyperparameter tuning, it had the highest R (0.94) and the lowest MSE, making it the most robust choice. It reduces overfitting compared to a single decision tree and captures complex patterns in the data.

    2. Refined Insights:¶

    Feature Importance: The top features influencing the car price were found to be Power, Year, Engine, Mileage, and Kilometers_Driven. This suggests that car performance metrics and the age of the vehicle are critical in determining its price.

    Log Transformation: Applying log transformations helped normalize skewed distributions, which in turn improved model performance, particularly for linear models.

    Outlier Management: Addressing outliers, particularly in the Price variable across different Locations, was crucial in refining model accuracy.

    3. Proposal for the Final Solution Design:¶

    Recommended Model: The Random Forest Regressor is recommended as the final model for predicting used car prices. It consistently outperformed other models in terms of accuracy (R), and it handled the complexities and non-linearities in the data well.

    Reasoning: The models robustness against overfitting, ability to handle a large number of features, and effectiveness with both categorical and numerical data make it the best choice for this problem. The slight performance improvement post-tuning also indicates that this model is well-optimized for the task.

    Further Recommendations:¶

    Model Deployment: Consider deploying the Random Forest model as a web service or API for the Cars 4U platform to predict car prices dynamically.

    Continuous Learning: As more data becomes available, retraining the model periodically can help maintain or even improve prediction accuracy.

    User Interface: Integrate the model with a user-friendly interface that allows users to input car details and receive instant price predictions.
